SIMPLE: intoxicate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Intoxicate
<hw>In*tox"i*cate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>intoxicatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>intoxicare</ets> to drug or
poison; pref. <ets>in-</ets> in + L. <ets>toxicum</ets> a poison in
which arrows were dipped, Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ pertaining to a bow. See
<er>Toxic</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Intoxicated.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Overexcited, as with joy or grief.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Alas, good mother, be not <qex>intoxicate</qex> for me;⟦br⟧
I am well enough.</q> <rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intoxicate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Intoxicate
<hw>In*tox"i*cate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Intoxicated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Intoxicating</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To poison; to drug.</def>
<rj><au>South.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make drunk; to inebriate; to excite or to stupefy
by strong drink or by a narcotic substance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With new wine <qex>inoxicated</qex> both.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To excite to a transport of enthusiasm, frenzy, or
madness; to elate unduly or excessively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Intoxicated</qex> with the sound of those very bells.</q>
<rj><qau>G. Eliot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They are not <qex>intoxicated</qex> by military success.</q>
<rj><qau>Jowett (Thuc.).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intoxicatedness</ent>⟦br⟧
